Under the above optimal conditions, the detection of Cd2+ based on the sensing system were investigated. As presented in Fig. 5
                        A, the fluorescence intensity of HRGO-AuNCs was gradually increased with the concentration of Cd2+. Moreover, as exhibited in Fig. 5B, the fluorescence enhancement efficiency ((F-F0)/F0
                        ) was closely related with Cd2+ concentration and it displays good linear relationship between fluorescence enhancement efficiency and Cd2+ concentration in the range of 0.1-100 μM. The linear regression equations were (F-F
                        0
                        )/F
                        0 = 0.1409[Cd2+]+0.1019 and (F-F
                        0
                        )/F
                        0 = 0.0183[Cd2+]+0.8699 in the ranges of 0.1–6 μM (R2 = 0.9997) and 6–100 μM (R2 = 0.9989), respectively. The detection limit was about 42.0 nM, which was better than many of the previous reports for Cd2+ determination (Table S1). In this work, the detection of Cd2+ was realized by the formation of Cd-GSH complex on the AuNCs surface which can increase the distance between the HRGO and AuNCs and induce the fluorescence recovery. To this end, the concentration of Cd2+ and the reaction sites on GSH-AuNCs both can affect the reaction speed and the detection sensitivity. In the lower concentration of Cd2+, it is more sensitive because of more reaction sites and more opportunities for the reaction chance for the Cd2+ and GSH-AuNCs. And when the concentration increased to certain extent, some of the activity sites of the GSH-AuNCs are occupied and the reaction chance declined which will decrease the detection sensitivity. Therefore, two linear parts appeared during the detection process.
